{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491183"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:36:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:36:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"858"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/858"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.5,0.08,0.19,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"858"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92488"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/858"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"858"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75798"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"108"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13180"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31163"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92488"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman who recently migrated from India presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of crampy, generalised abdominal pain and diarrhoea. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her abdomen is soft with mild tenderness in the left lower quadrant. A plain abdominal X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organisms is most likely responsible for the radiographic changes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Escherichia coli","Mycobacterium tuberculosis","Leishmaniasis donovani","Schistosoma mansoni","Wuchereria bancrofti"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETwo calcified lymph nodes are visible on the X-ray. The most common cause for such calcification is previous exposure to \u003Cstrong\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E, which is highly prevalent in endemic countries like India. Abdominal involvement occurs in 11-16% of patients with extra-pulmonary tuberculosis, with lymphadenopathy being the most common manifestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/strong\u003E infection typically causes acute gastroenteritis but does not lead to lymph node calcification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeishmaniasis donovani\u003C/strong\u003E can cause hepatosplenomegaly and lymphadenopathy but rarely causes calcification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchistosoma mansoni\u003C/strong\u003E infection can cause calcifications, but these are typically seen in the bladder wall or ureters rather than lymph nodes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWuchereria bancrofti\u003C/strong\u003E causes lymphatic filariasis but does not typically result in calcified lymph nodes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical manifestations of abdominal tuberculosis vary depending on the organ involvement. Intestinal tuberculosis can present with abdominal pain, distention, chronic diarrhoea, nausea, vomiting, constipation or bleeding. This reflects ulcero-constrictive disease requiring anti-tuberculous therapy. Surgery may be needed for complications like perforation, abscess formation, obstruction, or fistulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient\u0027s recent migration from India, drug-resistant tuberculosis should be considered. Drug susceptibility testing of cultured samples is essential to guide antimicrobial therapy, and involvement of infectious diseases specialists is recommended.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Previous exposure to tuberculosis commonly causes lymph node calcification on abdominal X-ray.","Abdominal tuberculosis affects 11-16% of patients with extra-pulmonary tuberculosis, with lymphadenopathy being the most common manifestation.","Recent migrants from high-burden countries should be assessed for drug-resistant tuberculosis strains."],"references":["Ganchua SKC, White AG, Klein EC, et al. Lymph nodes\u2014The neglected battlefield in tuberculosis. PLoS Pathog 2020; 16: e1008632."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75798"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"858"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"180"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/180"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/755884d7-52f5-4998-9a93-4078379c68ee.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/755884d7-52f5-4998-9a93-4078379c68ee.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":347,"height":420}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75798"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-17T23:43:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T21:08:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"858"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92488"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"s